    "hc_clothes_smell_xrBYE4": {
      "type": "hc-clothes-smell",
      "name": "HC Clothes Smell",
      "settings": {
        "story_anchor_id": "our-story",
        "mission_anchor_id": "our-mission",
        "eyebrow": "Iceland, 2017",
        "heading": "Why do clothes smell?",
        "story_content": "<p>A few months before the trip, Wen, our founder, lost his mom.</p><p>He needed to get away. So he packed a backpack — just a few pieces of clothing — and flew to Iceland.</p><p>He wasn't there to be productive. He was there to breathe, to be somewhere completely different, and hopefully, to feel something other than grief for a little while. His friends were there too, and they wanted to go out — explore, party, live. He wanted that too. More than they probably knew.</p><p>But Iceland had other plans.</p><p>Within days, some of his clothes started smelling. Not subtly — noticeably. The strange thing was, other pieces were completely fine. Same backpack, same trip, same person wearing them. Why were some clothes unbearable after a single wear while others stayed fresh?</p><p>He didn't have a good answer. And he didn't have a laundromat either — their hostel didn't have one, and if you've spent time in Iceland, you already know they're not exactly on every corner. So he did what anyone would do: reached for the cologne, leaned on the deodorant, and tried to convince himself it wasn't that bad.</p><p>It was that bad.</p><p>One by one, evenings he'd planned to spend out with friends became evenings spent in — not because he wanted to, but because he couldn't shake the self-consciousness of knowing he didn't smell great. It sounds small. But when you've traveled thousands of miles to feel alive again, being sidelined by a t-shirt is its own particular kind of defeat.</p><p>On the way home, somewhere over the Atlantic, the question finally crystallized:</p><p><strong>Why do clothes smell? And do they actually have to?</strong></p><p>It felt almost too simple. But he couldn't let it go. Back home, he started digging — into bacteria, enzymes, airflow, material science, fiber construction. He tested yarns, fabrics, and treatments. He failed a lot. He learned more. Two years later, what started as a question on a grief trip to Iceland had become something he hadn't expected:</p><p><strong>A mission. A company. A reason to keep going.</strong></p>",
        "show_mission_card": true,
        "mission_eyebrow": "Our Mission",
        "mission_heading_line1": "To free humanity through",
        "mission_heading_line2": "the power of our fibers.",
        "beliefs_label": "Our Beliefs",
        "belief_1": "Clothes are costing us more than money.\nThey're costing us time, space, energy,\npeace of mind, and our freedom.\nWorse of all, they're destroying our planet.",
        "belief_2": "The world doesn't need more clothes.\nIt needs better ones, clothes that do more with less.\nLess washing. Less waste. Less weight on the planet.",
        "belief_3": "Every thing we make is a step toward that world.",
        "footer_note": "Together, our mission and beliefs became the foundation of HercLeón.",
        "padding_top_mobile": 64,
        "padding_bottom_mobile": 64,
        "padding_top_desktop": 128,
        "padding_bottom_desktop": 128
      }
    },
